alfe-conformance — scenario corpus, parity tests, spec maintenance
==================================================================

See also: alfe.plan, alfe-cli.issue, alfe-backend-clautolisp.issue,
alfe-backend-bricscad.issue, alfe-backend-autocad.issue,
spec section "Invariants testés".

Context
-------

The legacy `autolisp-script` ships a body of invariants tested
against real AutoCAD/BricsCAD on Windows plus the in-process
clautolisp backend. alfe must reproduce those invariants and add
its own, plus a *parity test* layer that compares alfe's behaviour
to the bash wrapper for the same input. This issue is the backbone
quality work that runs alongside every implementation ticket.

In scope
--------

  1. Scenario corpus. Mirror the layout of
     `clautolisp/autolisp-file-compat/scenarios/` :

         autolisp-front-end/tests/scenarios/
             cli/             argument parsing and exit codes
             actions/         -x / -l / --main behaviour
             interactive/     multi-line REPL forms
             encoding/        UTF-8 / ISO-8859-1 / Windows-1252 × LF/CRLF/CR
             file-protocol/   atomic-publish, status polling, line→form
             bricscad/        bricscad-specific invariants
             autocad/         autocad-specific invariants

     Each scenario is a `.sexp` declaration (matches the existing
     autolisp-file-compat shape): name, classification (`:portable`,
     `:bricscad-only`, `:autocad-only`, `:clautolisp-only`), action
     plan, expected stdout/stderr fragments, expected exit code,
     optional setup-files. CAD-bound scenarios are tagged so the
     runner skips them when no engine is available.

  2. Runner. A small CL tool under
     `autolisp-front-end/tools/run-alfe-conformance/` that walks
     scenarios, invokes alfe with the declared CLI, captures
     output/exit, and emits a `report.sexp` (and optional `report.json`)
     consistent with `clautolisp/autolisp-file-compat`'s report format.
     `make -C autolisp-front-end test` invokes this runner with the
     mocked-backend subset by default.

  3. Parity tests. A scenario classification `:parity` declares a
     legacy `autolisp` invocation and an `alfe` invocation that
     should produce equivalent stdout / stderr / exit code (modulo
     documented divergences, captured per-scenario as a
     `:tolerated-divergence` plist). When the legacy bash wrapper
     is reachable on the host (env var `AUTOLISP_LEGACY=path/to/autolisp`),
     the runner executes both sides and diffs.

  4. Spec maintenance. The spec under
     `autolisp-front-end/documentation/alfe--specifications.org`
     stays the source of truth. Every implementation ticket must
     update the corresponding spec section before merging. This
     issue tracks the meta-rule: a `scripts/check-spec-coverage.lisp`
     helper walks the spec for option names and asserts that every
     CLI option mentioned is exercised by at least one scenario.

  5. CI integration:
       - Default lane: `make test` from the repo root runs the
         mocked-backend subset of the conformance corpus ;
       - Optional lane: `BRICSCAD_SMOKE=1` and `AUTOCAD_SMOKE=1`
         opt-in the real-CAD scenarios; CI fails loudly when an
         opt-in lane runs without the env var, so a real CAD host
         in CI can be added later without touching the runner.
       - Parity lane: `AUTOLISP_LEGACY=...` opt-in runs the parity
         scenarios against a co-located bash wrapper checkout.

  6. Builtin coverage tracker (out-of-scope-stub). A sibling of
     `clautolisp/tools/builtins-coverage/` ; sketches an alfe-side
     view of "which CLI options + which env vars have at least one
     scenario covering them". Optional; implement only if the
     manual map starts to drift.

Out of scope
------------

  - Adding tests for behaviour that the implementation tickets
    haven't shipped yet. This issue *runs alongside* the other
    tickets and absorbs scenarios as they become exercisable.
  - Performance benchmarks. Worth a separate issue if performance
    parity with the bash wrapper becomes contentious.

Acceptance criteria
-------------------

  - The runner produces a green report on the mocked-backend
    subset, on every commit, with no flake under load.
  - Every option in the spec is referenced by at least one scenario
    (asserted by `scripts/check-spec-coverage.lisp`).
  - At least one parity scenario per action class (`-x`, `-l`,
    `--main`, `-i`) passes against a current legacy bash checkout.
  - `make -C autolisp-front-end test` invokes the runner and surfaces
    failures with file:line:scenario-name in the CI log.

Notes
-----

Treat this issue as a backbone: every other alfe-* ticket should
land at least one scenario and one spec update as part of its
acceptance criteria, even if it duplicates a CL unit test inside
that ticket's own test file. Belt-and-braces is fine; the spec
coverage check is what catches drift.
